You may not know this about me but I'm a self professed queen of free & thrifty! I've been thrifting for decades, long before there were on-line sources with incredible finds. Slide for some in our living room:

1. The amazing 80" long French button tufted sofa found in a thrift for $150 which I had recovered. 
2. Wood mantel ripped out of a client's home who was redecorating - free to me.
3. Fireplace screen was a headboard on a damaged French bed (free) and I cut & painted it to use as you see it. 
4. French mirror found on Craigslist for $125. 
And...I could go on and on room by room!

Today on the blog I have an article about REDECORATING YOUR HOME FOR FREE that has TONS of IDEAS and links! 

If you'd like the link to the post sent to your inbox just comment - FREE and I'll send it your way. 

I have ALWAYS believed that any home decorator can have a beautiful space with any budget that is your situation! 

Thanks for being here and enjoy your day!
xo, Janet

My home didn’t always look like this (slide) and today marks a day in history that I’d rather forget.

In the other images you’ll see my 2 innocent young girls sitting and coloring the day before disaster struck. 

In the other shots was the aftermath of Hurricane Andrew, 31 years ago today. 

To say that was disaster doesn’t even begin to cover the emotions of having a monster storm make a direct hit on your home and surrounding neighbor’s homes. It was traumatic and yet we decided to stay and rebuild. 
Today I’m thinking about that fateful day (we had no power for a month) and how far we’ve come over the years since. I would not wish this for anyone and my heart (and wallet) goes out to the disaster victims and their families in the Hawaï fires. Let’s do what we can to help with a grateful ❤️

I’m so ready for fall 🍁(are you?)

My fall living room tour for this year is live on the blog today! Swipe through for some images & then if you’d like a direct link, comment LINK or see my stories.

Have you picked up Ralph Lauren’s latest coffee table book yet? I have and it’s massive, so I haven’t gotten through it yet. Beautiful though and he speaks to the heart! I particularly like this thought (abbreviated) regarding design of your home style: “Living without boundaries with the things that you love, guided only by your heart 🤎 and what inspires your eye.” 
Thoughts my friends?

I interrupt this fall to talk about style and color for a minute! 

Some random shots from my home that show a common theme and color. Repeating colors and patterns is one of the easiest and most effective ways to unify your home, especially in an open floor plan. I choose blue and one of my favorite things about the blue family is the wide range of tonality from the palest color of the sky to the blue/green of the Florida seas to deepest navy. I have even gone with blue for quite a few Christmas seasons and debating doing it again this year! 

Are you a fan of blue too or what’s your favorite color to carry through your home? 

Slide order:
1. My vintage rattan roll top desk found on FBMP for $40 and it was already painted in this yummy cream neutral! Lots of blue accents and this is a corner in the living room by the bay window where I often sit and work. 

2. The world’s longest hallway leading from the family room to our primary suite. We made the grasscloth covered table from scratch (tutorial on my blog), the Chinoiserie framed wall panels and vintage pieces on the table. 

3. Front foyer with a console marriage that we custom made flanked by a painted antique pier mirror. 

4. A vintage dry sink that we converted into a bar (diy on the blog) with rattan and other cool accents. 

5. My office, which also serves as a guest room with a yummy pale blue velvet sofa bed. Let me know if you’d like the source or any sources!

6.  The laundry room that has me in love with doing laundry! Ceramic wall tiles and tropical accents brighten things up in this large windowless space. 

Hope you enjoy your weekend and keep checking my stories for something happening over here!

So, last year our Christmas decor was pretty nil, since we were smack dab in the middle of our complete kitchen renovation! We took out all of the soffits in-between the kitchen and family room and it really opened up the family room, which works so much better. 

You know how one things can lead to another in renovation, so we took out the wall unit on one side, and reused the bottom portion as the media cabinet that you see. Then we decided to sell the furniture on FBMP and got this comfy pair of deep seated slipcovered sofas! Works for us so much better now.

My Christmas home from previous years and this year is much more “quiet”! There are so many beautifully styled and shot holiday homes on IG this year and to be honest I feel like I can’t keep up. Or maybe don’t want to and crave and implementing a more simple approach these days. After all, it’s about family moments and I so look forward to having the nest full for the holidays! 

Thanks so much for being here & Happy Holidays! 🎄💕 Janet
